al14\n	val2	val21\n	val5	val51\n\nthen:\n	select col00, col01 from table00 group by col00;\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-17 14:28:44'),(371,'mariadb','community-developed fork of the MySQL intended to remain free under the GNU GPL',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-17 14:38:07'),(372,'notable','remarkable, Worthy of attention or notice; ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-17 14:39:10'),(373,'#vim #range #put',NULL,NULL,'\n:put =range(5, 17)\n	it will create sth like this:\n	5\n	6\n	7\n	8\n	...\n	17\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-17 15:24:07'),(374,'#vim #for #range #put',NULL,NULL,'\n:for i in range(1,10) | put =\'192.168.0.\'.i | endfor\n	192.168.0.1\n	192.168.0.2\n	192.168.0.3\n	192.168.0.4\n	192.168.0.5\n	192.168.0.6\n	192.168.0.7\n	192.168.0.8\n	192.168.0.9\n	192.168.0.10\n\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-17 15:37:58'),(377,'#vim #show#all#map',NULL,NULL,':map\n	displays the maps that work in normal, visual and select mode\n:map!\n	displays the maps that work in insert and command-line mode\n\n:nmap - Display normal mode maps\n:imap - Display insert mode maps\n:vmap - Display visual and select mode maps\n:smap - Display select mode maps\n:xmap - Display visual mode maps\n:cmap - Display command-line mode maps\n:omap - Display operator pending mode maps\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-17 15:56:58'),(378,'#vim #analysing#result :map',NULL,NULL,'\n:nmap\nn  <C-W>*      * <C-W><C-S>*\nn  <C-W>#      * <C-W><C-S>#\nn  <F2>        * :lchdir %:p:h<CR>:pwd<CR>\n\nn  Normal mode map. Defined using \':nmap\' or \':nnoremap\'.\n\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-17 16:06:08'),(376,'#vim #keymap #mapping#intro','\nKey mapping refers to creating a shortcut for repeating a sequence of keys or command\nex:\n	:map <F2> :echo \'Current time is \' . strftime(\'%c\')<CR>\n		then, when u hit <f2> sth like will appear where u have to enter cmd\n			Sat 17 Jan 2015 17:42:42 SAST		\n	but\n	:map! <F2> :echo \'Current time is \' . strftime(\'%c\')<CR>\n		will appear the result in the current_buffer\n\nThe first step is to decide the sequence of keys that needs to be mapped.\n\nsecond step is instead of creating a map that works in all the modes, it is better to define the map that works only in selected modes.\n\nThe third step is to find an unused key sequence that can be used to invoke the map\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-17 15:50:40'),(379,'#vim #redirection',NULL,NULL,'\nwhen u do some cmd in vim, the result can _span_ several pages, ie the result is too long\n  so u have to put the result inside a file\n	:redir! > vim_maps.txt\n	:map\n	:map!\n	:redir END\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-18 04:00:52'),(380,'#vim #unmap',NULL,NULL,'\nonly one example\n\n	:unmap <F3>\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-18 04:02:11'),(381,'#language #japanese #types','Three types of character sets\n    Hiragana,\n    Katakana \n    Kanji\n  are used in a mixed way. You need to know around 2,000 letters to read publications. It can take several years to learn them.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-19 07:41:58'),(382,'#mysql #create #db #database',NULL,'make sure that u are in root of mysql\n  mysql> create database db00;',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-19 08:22:16'),(383,'application_reseau #definition #network','Une application est l\'utilisation (voire l\'exploitation) d\'une ressource pour en faire quelque chose de concret.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-19 09:08:00'),(384,'#biggest#network in the#world','reseau internet\nreseau telecom',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-19 09:10:23'),(385,'#definition #network #www','ensembles des sites web presents sur internet',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-19 09:12:00'),(386,'#definition#internet #network','l\'ensemble des nœuds (connexions, câbles, etc.) entre les machines qui nous donnent accès au web\n  il y a bcp d_autre chose sur internet mais pas seulement du web',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-19 09:33:13'),(387,'#definition#reseau_internet #network','Le réseau Internet est le réseau permettant la communication entre différents ordinateurs connectés à Internet',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-19 09:14:37'),(388,'#network #introduction definition','\nUn réseau est un groupe de chose|entités en communication(qui parlent entre eux).\n	attention:	\n		il y a plusieurs entitees\n		il y a plusieurs facons de faire la communication\nle principe d_intermediaire est le _fondement_ des ppe du reseau\n\npour communiquer, les 2choses doivent parler la meme langue(protocole)\nOU\nl_intermediaire doit parler la meme langue(protocole) de chacun de ses interlocuteurs\n\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-19 09:19:18'),(389,'#network #tip #network','qui dit reseau, dit _assurer|faire_ la communication',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-19 09:23:28'),(390,'#network #definition #intro #internet','interconnected computers which all use tcp_ip to communicate\n  all web-servers which have sites __publicly accessible__ are a part of the internet\n  it is not only web service the service that internet can give, there are many\n  all materials which can access internet is a part of internet as well :/\nIn the real Internet, dozens of large Internet providers interconnect at NAPs in various cities,\nThe Internet is a collection of huge corporate networks that agree to all intercommunicate with each other at the NAPs. In this way, every computer on the Internet connects to every other\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-20 03:03:42'),(391,'#network #intro_ssl&http&https','HTTP, is the language or “protocol” spoken by all web browsers when they communicate with web servers.\nSecure Sockets Layer (SSL) is a protocol that provides secure communication.\nWhen two programs communicate with each other using HTTP via SSL,\n	it is referred to as “HTTPS”\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-19 10:52:59'),(392,'#network #intro_dns_dynamic','\ncomputers are given a different IP address every time they connect to the Internet.\nThis practice allows Internet service providers (ISPs) to serve many customers using only a few IP addresses\nif users host a website in that isp, the isp needs dns_dynamic for updating automatically the relationship between their fixed website name and the changing IP address, so that their website is easy to find on the Internet.\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-19 11:09:53'),(393,'#network #cable#types #ethernet #croisee #droit #rj45 #rj11','\ncable ethernet: rj45 est l_interface\n	appellee aussi utp-cat5 ou utp-cat6\n		la cat6 supporte qlq gigabit par sec\n		la cat5 supporte 100megabits par sec\n	2types:\n		croisees, dit aussi cable batard:\n			ordi ordi\n		droit:\n			ordi a une autre appareil(pas ordi)\ncable telephonique = rj11 est l_interface\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-19 11:10:20'),(394,'#network #intro dns','a dns is a db\nit stores all of the domain names and corresponding IP address  for a specific top-level domain (TLD) ex_of_tld:.com .gov .org\nit is addressing a sys to internet\nWithin every top-level domain there is a huge list of second-level domains. For example, in the .COM first-level domain there is:\n    HowStuffWorks\n    Yahoo\n    Microsoft\nEvery name in the .COM top-level domain must be unique\nThe left-most word, like www, is the host name. It specifies the name of a specific machine in a domain with a specific IP\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-20 19:55:08'),(395,'#network #basic #intro#structure','\nthe must known about the structure of the internet are:\n	dns\n	network access pt\n	backbones\n\nevery computer connected to the internet are a part of the internet\ninternet is a network of network >.<\n\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-19 11:41:37'),(396,'#network #definition #pop','point of presence\n  Most large communications companies have their own dedicated backbones connecting various regions. In each region, the company has a Point of Presence (POP). The POP is a place for local users to access the company\'s network, often through a local phone number or dedicated line',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-19 11:45:08'),(397,'#vim #drawit','\nit is used to draw in vim with:\n	left - right - down - up\nhttp://www.vim.org/scripts/script.php?script_id=40\n\njust dl the \"DrawIt.vba.gz\" and go in the folder by terminal where u dldd it\nread it like this: \n	vi DrawIt.vba.gz \n	in vim do\n		:so %\n		sometimes it doesn_t work at first time then repeat again\n	and quit bcz it is already installed\n		:q	\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-19 11:59:21'),(398,'#network #introduction #backbone #pop #architecture','\nMost large communications companies have their own dedicated backbones connecting various regions.\nIn each region, the company has a Point of Presence (POP)\nThe POP is a place for local users to access the company\'s network\n\n\n                                                                                     \n                                                             +--------I S P--------+\n                                     +----I S P----+         |+-------------------+|\n  +---+      +---------+             |  +-------+  |         || +---------------+ ||<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<< \n  +---+      |  home   +<-+--------->+  |  pop  |<<<<--+---->>>>+      nap      | ||            I N T E R N E T\n /___/       +---------+  |          |  +----^--+  |   |     || +---------------+ ||+++<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<\n                          |          +-------^-----+   |     |+-------------------+| |\n                          |                  ^         |     +---------------------+ |\n          +---------------+---+              |         |   +-------+                 |\n          |conventional_phone |              |         +---+t3_line|                 |\n          |cable_modem_line   |              |             +-------+                 +---+   +---------------+ \n          |digital_subscriber |              |                                           |   | +-----------+ | \n          +-------------------+              |       +-------+                           +---+ + BACKBONE  | | \n                                             +-------|t1_line|                               | +-----------+ | \n                                             |       +-------+                               +---------------+ \n                                             |                                                                 \n                 +------------+              |\n                 |+----------+|              |\n                 ||   lan    ++<-------------+\n        +---+----++----------+|\n        |   |    +-------+----+\n      +-+   |       +----+---+\n  +---+     |     +-+        +--+\n  +---+     |     |          +--+\n /___/   +--+     +--+      /___/\n         +--+     +--+\n         \\___    \\___\n\n\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-20 22:07:48'),(399,'bsd #intro #unix','\nBSD ne sont pas des clones, mais des dérivés Open Source du système d\'exploitation UNIX® issus des laboratoires de recherche de AT&T, qui est lui-même un ancêtre de l\'actuel UNIX® System V\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-19 20:14:31'),(400,'#network #intro#nap','\nall of Company A\'s customers can talk to each other, and all of Company B\'s customers can talk to each other, but there is no way for Company A\'s customers and Company B\'s customers to intercommunicate. Therefore, Company A and Company B both agree to connect to NAPs in various cities, and traffic between the two companies flows between the networks at the NAPs.\n                            +-------------------+                          +-----------------------+\n                            |                   |                          |                       |\n                            |                   |                          |                       |\n                            |                   |                          |                       |\n                            |                   |                          |                       |\n                            |                   |                          |                       |\n                            |    compA_network  +<------------------------>+                       |\n                            |                   |        nap               | comp B_network        |\n                            |                   +<------------------------>+                       |\n                            |                   |                          |                       |\n                            |                   |                          |                       |\n                            |                   |                          |                       |\n                            |                   |                          |                       |\n                           -+-------------------+                          +-----------------------+\n\nIn the real Internet, dozens of large Internet providers interconnect at NAPs in various cities,\nThe Internet is a collection of huge corporate networks that agree to all intercommunicate with each other at the NAPs\nAll of these networks rely on NAPs, backbones and routers to talk to each other.\nThe routers determine where to send information from one computer to another\nA router has two separate, but related, jobs:\n	It ensures that information doesn\'t go where it\'s not needed\n	It makes sure that information does make it to the intended destination\n\na router is extremely useful in dealing with two separate computer networks.\nIt also protects the networks from one another, preventing the traffic on one from unnecessarily _spilling_ over to the other.\n\n                                                            |  I  |\n                                                            |  N  |\n                                                            |  T  |\n                                                            v  E  v\n                +-----------+                               v  R  v                              +-------------+\n                |  pc_1     |                               v  N  v                              |   pc_1      |\n                |  pc_2     |                               v  E  v                  +-----------+   pc_2      |\n                |           +---------+               +-----v  T  v -----+           |           |             |\n                |           |         |               |  +--+-----+--+   |           |           |             |\n                |  netw_A   |       +-+-------+       |  |           |   |       +---+--+        |   netw_B    |\n                |           +<----->+ switch  +<------+->+   ROUTER  +<--+------>+switch+<------>+             |\n                |           |       +-+-------+       |  |           |   |       +----+-+        |             |\n                |   pc_200  +---------+               |  +-----------+   |            |          |   pc100     |\n                |   pc_300  |                         +------------------+            +----------|   pc250     |\n                +-----------+                                                                    +-------------+\n\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-20 03:47:42'),(401,'#latex #introduction','\nlatex et html possedent des similitudes mais latex est consacree pour les publications scientifiques.\n	avec un excellent rendu des équations et formules\nIl permet également de générer facilement sommaires, listes de figures et numéros d\'équation\nLes fichiers LaTeX peuvent ensuite être convertis en un grand nombre de formats différents comme par exemple PDF, PostScript, DVI, et HTML\n\nse prononce \"latec\" ou \"latheque\" mais surtout pas \"latex\"\n\nUn fichier LaTeX est un fichier contenant du _texte_ et des commandes de marquage. \nil est ensuite converti vers d\'autres formats grâce à un compilateur LaTeX.\n\ncertains utilisent __texmaker__ ou __kile__ pour faire du latex\ncertains utilisent les bon_editeurs du texte comme vim, emacs, gedit, .....\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-20 10:45:09'),(402,'#zip#explore',NULL,NULL,'this is how to #see explore inside of file00.zip\n    unzip -l file00.zip',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-20 10:56:14'),(403,'#introduction #latex #dldd #documentation','\nwhen u dldd a file for help and tuto for latex:  http://www.howtotex.com/download/FiveMinuteGuideToLaTeX.zip\n	hope that link still work when u read this doc\n3subfolders are present:\n	docs\n		contains the main content and the preamble for the documentation\n	figs\n		where all figures are placed\n	refs\n		contains a file for the bibliography\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-20 11:01:57'),(404,'#tree #linux #intro','\ndisplays directory tree, in color\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-20 11:11:41'),(405,'#latex #intro #ifk','\nfirst thing u have to do with latex is to do the \"preamble\"\n	which mean to define the class of the document\n		ex: article, book, report, slides, letter\n	and to define some __optional__ arguments, \n		ex: font_size\n	example of preamble:\n		\\documentclass[10pt]{report}\n		% documentclass is a keyword\n		% {} is to define the class chosen\n		% [] is to define the font_size\n\nthen comes the \"environment\"\n	everything content should be done inside\n		\\begin{}\n		\\end{}\n		% {} contains the environment_name\n		% 	here are some environment:\n		% 		math, figures, tables, .........\n	__warning__:\n	everything inside the \\begin{} and \\end\n		will be printed\n	\nafter that the \"sectioning\"\n	A distinct part or subdivision of a writing is created with:\n		\\section{} , \\subsection{} , \\subsubsection{} , \\paragraph{}\n		, where {} contains the title.\n	The report and book classes require an additional \\chapter{} command\n\nin latex: {} will define many things\n	it is up to the section where u are in\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-20 11:36:28'),(406,'#latex #comment','\nthese are some examples for comments in latex:\n        % this is comment in latex which should be only one line\n\n        \\begin{comment}\n        here is a very long comment\n        \\end{comment}\n\n        \\/*\n        here is another long line of comment\n        potatoes\n        mangoes\n        */\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-20 11:47:52'),(407,'#vim #escaping #\\','\nto escape \\\n	ex: :%s/\\\\/\\\\\\\\/cg\nyes, that is right\n  that_s how to change all \\ to \\\\',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-20 11:41:05'),(408,'#zathura #conf #linux',NULL,NULL,'~/.zathurarcm/etc/zathurarc',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-20 13:46:20'),(409,'#linux #log #some #general','\n/var/log/messages – Contains global system messages\n/var/log/dmesg\n	When the system boots up, it prints number of messages on the screen\n		These messages are available in _kernel ring buffer_\n	this file contains kernel ring buffer information.\n	whenever the new message comes the old message gets overwritten.\n	u can check the content of this file by doing:	dmesg\n/var/log/auth.log\n/var/log/boot.log\n/var/log/aptitude\n	log of cmd which installed sth in ur sys by aptitude_cmd\n/var/log/apt/history.log\n	when a cmd uses apt-get for installing a packet\n		the log will be in this file\n/var/log/apt/term.log\n	this is the _process_ of installation of packet\n/var/log/lastlog\n	Displays the recent login information for all the users.\n	but I don_t understand why mine doesn_t work, kali\n\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-20 19:53:08'),(410,'#network #intro dns','\nLet\'s say that you type the URL www.howstuffworks.com into your browser.\nThe browser contacts a _your(ifk)_ DNS server to get the IP address of www.howstuffworks.com . \nA DNS server would start its search for an IP address by contacting one of the __root_DNS_servers__.\n	The root servers know the IP addresses of servers which handle the top-level domains (.COM, .NET, .ORG, etc.)\n	The root says, I don\'t know the IP address for www.howstuffworks.com\n	but here\'s the IP address for the .COM DNS server.\n\n_Your_name_server_ then sends a query to the .COM DNS server asking it if it knows the IP address for www.howstuffworks.com.\nThe_DNS_server for the .COM domain knows the IP addresses for the name_servers_handling_the_www.howstuffworks.com \n	::::so it returns those to ur dns_server::::: :)\nand ur dns_server would return that to ur browser\nthen ur browser can get the web which u_were asking for\n\nOnce it has made a request to a root DNS server for any .COM domain,r\n  	ur dns_server knows the IP address for a DNS server handling the .COM\n	so it doesn\'t have to bug the root DNS servers again for that information\n	::that is called caching::\n\nDNS servers handle billions of requests every day, and they are essential to the internet_s smooth functioning\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-20 21:37:21'),(411,'#network #introduction #internet #server#client','\nAll of the machines on the Internet are either servers or clients\nmachine which provides services for other machine are called _server_\nmachines that are used to connect to those services are clients\nThere are Web servers, e-mail servers, FTP servers\n	and so on\n\nWhen you connect to www.howstuffworks.com to read a page, you are a user sitting at a client\'s machine\n	accessing the HowStuffWorks Web server. \n	A web server is a just a computer program that listens for requests from browsers and then execute them\nClients that come to a server machine do so with a specific intent,\n	so clients direct their requests to a specific software server running on the server machine.\n	For example, if you are running a Web browser on your machine,\n		it will want to talk to the Web server on the server machine, not the e-mail server\n\nA server has a static IP address that does not change very often. \nA home machine that is dialing up through a modem,\n	on the other hand, typically has an IP address assigned by the ISP every time you dial in.\n	it may be different the next time you dial in\n	That IP address is unique for your session\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-20 23:12:18'),(412,'payload #definition #general','The actual information or message in transmitted data, as opposed to automatically generated metadata',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-20 23:29:25'),(413,'#network #introduction #http','\nA web server is a just a computer program that listens for requests from browsers and then execute them. \nwhen u direct ur browser to a link, the link may direct to(html_page, zip_file, pdf, ....)\n	the browser will show the document with the program it was configured to\n	The browser will display HTML documents directly\n\nhttp is a protocol in the application_layer which is used to transfer data on the web\n                                                                                \nhttp is a request-response protocol\n	For example, a Web browser initiates a request to a server,\n	typically by opening a TCP/IP connection.\n\nThe request(from the client) itself contains:\n	a request_line\n		ex:	GET /index.php HTTP/1.1\n	a __set__ of request header\n	an entity\n\nthe response (from server) contains:\n	a status line\n	a set of response headers\n	an entity\n\nthe entity can be thought as the payload which may be a binary_data\n	but the other items are ascii_characters\n\nexample: client wants to connect to site00.com\n	browser sends:\n		GET / HTTP/1.1				-- request line\n			--	GET:	so the server is supposed to return an entity\n			--	/ :		an uri,	The / indicates the root of the document system on the server\n			--	HTTP/1.1	the prot and the version\n\n		Connection: Keep-Alive\n			-- this means that the client to keep the connection after the response of the server\n		User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (compatible; Konqueror/2.2-11; Linux) \n			-- this is optional\n		\n		Accept: text/*, image/jpeg, image/png, image/*, */*\n		Accept-Encoding: x-gzip, gzip, identity\n		Accept-Charset: Any, utf-8, *\n		Accept-Language: en, en_US\n		Host: www.silicon-press.com\n			--\n			-- specify the type, language , and encoding\n			-- 	for the returned entity\n			--	that the browser would prefer to receive \n			--	from the server \n	Responding to the browser, the www.site00.com server sends the following response \n		HTTP/1.1 200 OK\n			-- the version of the http used\n			-- 200:	a status code\n			-- OK:	a short description of the status code\n\n		Date: Thu, 24 Jan 2002 17:33:52 GMT\n			-- ifk: this is the datetime when the server send this response\n		Server: Apache/1.3.14\n			-- ifk: information about the web_server\n		Last-Modified: Mon, 21 Jan 2002 22:08:33 GMT\n			-- dunno\n		Etag: “47bc6-25e0-3c4c9161”          ---+\n		Accept-Ranges: bytes                    |    +----------------------------+\n		Content-Length: 9696                 ---+--->|describe the entity returned|\n		Connection: close                       |    +----------------------------+\n		Content-Type: text/html              ---+\n	',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-21 00:11:57'),(414,'#network #http #types_request','\nu should understand the id_n_t: 413 \nGET                                                                          \n	which means that the client require an entity from the server\nHEAD                                                                     \n	used to get back the response header only                            \nPOST                                                                     \n	used to submit data                                                  \nPUT                                                                      \n	used for uploading resource                                          \nPATCH                   \n    Is used to modify the resource                                                 \nDELETE\n	used to delete resource                                              \nTRACE                                                                    \n	This can be used for testing the servers and Checking whether the server is alive or not\nCONNECT                                                                  \n	Convert the transparent TCP/IP tunnel                                \n	usually to facilitate SSL encrypted Communication(HTTPS) through an unencrypted HTTP proxy. \nOPTIONS\n	used to define the requests supported by the servers\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-21 00:31:39'),(415,'#browser #architecture #network','\nthe main components are:\n	\n             +--------------+                   +-------+\n             |user_interface+-----+             |d      |\n             +-------+------+     |             |a      |\n                     v            |             |t      |\n            +--------+------+     |             |a      |\n            |browser_engine +--->>>>>>----------+-      |\n            +---------+-----+     |             |p  i  n|\n                      v           |             |e  s  c|\n             +--------+-------+   |             |r  t  e|\n             |rendering_engine|   |             |s  a   |\n             +-+------+-------+   |             +-------+\n               v      v           +-----------------v\n      +--------+-+ +--+-------------------+   +-----+-------+\n      |networking| |javascript_interpreter|   | ui_backend  |\n      +----------+ +----------------------+   +-------------+\n\n\nThe user interface:\n	this includes the address bar, back/forward button,\n	Every part of the browser display except the window where you see the requested page\nThe browser engine:\n	marshals actions between the UI and the rendering engine\n	ifk: before a rendering is made, it has to be parsed by browser_engine\nrendering_engine:\n	 responsible for displaying requested content\n	 For example if the requested content is HTML, the rendering engine parses HTML and CSS, and displays the parsed content on the screen.\nnetworking:\n	using different implementations for different platform behind a platform-independent interface\nUI backend:\n	used for drawing basic widgets like combo boxes and windows.\nJavaScript interpreter.\n	Used to parse and execute JavaScript code\nData storage.\n	This is a persistence layer. The browser may need to save all sorts of data locally, such as cookies\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-21 00:54:36'),(416,'#network #proxy #introduction','\n\n\n                        <1>                       <2>\n                  +-----------------v      +----------------+\n                  ^              +--+------+---+            v\n              +---+---+          |+-----------+|          +-+----+\n              | client|          || P R O X Y ||          |server|\n              +-----+-+          ||S E R V E R||          +-+----+\n                    ^            |+-----------+|            v\n                    |            +---+------+--+            |\n                    +----------------+      ^---------------+\n                            <4>                     <3>\n\nthis is an example of web_proxy_server\n\n\n\n\n               <1>: get me sample.html       <2>: get me sample.html\n                      from xyz.com                 from xyz.com\n                  +-----------------v      +----------------+\n                  ^              +--+------+---+            v\n              +---+---+          |+-----------+|          +-+----+\n              | client|          || W  E  B   ||          |server|(xyz.com)\n              +-----+-+          ||P R O X Y  ||          +-+----+\n                    ^            |+-----------+|            v\n                    |            +---+------+--+            |\n                    +----------------+      ^---------------+\n                       <4>: i_ve fetched          <3>: sample.html\n                             sample.html                is here\n                              .take_it.\n\n\n\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-21 01:55:24'),(417,'#network #types#proxy','\nhttp://www.gohacking.com/what-is-proxy-server-and-how-it-works/\nthere are 3types of proxies:\n	1. Forward Proxies\n		like in id_n_t=416\n		the server has to _specify_ the resources to be fetched\n			and the server_target to connect to\n\n	2. Open Proxy - has 3 types:\n		+intro:\n			a type of forwarding proxy\n			openly available to any internet_user\n			Most often, an open proxy is used by Internet users to conceal their IP address so that they remain anonymous during their web activity\n		+Anonymous Proxy\n			a type of open proxy that conceals IP address of Internet users so that the target server cannot identify the origin of the requesting client\n			an anonymous proxy identifies itself as a proxy server\n			manages to maintain the anonymity of the users\n		+Distorting Proxy\n			This type of proxy server identifies itself as a proxy, but reveals an incorrect IP address of the client to the target server\n		+High Anonymity Proxy (Elite Proxy)\n			it neither identifies itself as a proxy nor reveals the original IP address of the client\n			In most cases, users have to pay for this type of proxy\n	3. Reverse Proxy\n		a reverse proxy appears to the client as an ordinary server.\n		However, when the client requests resources from this server, it forwards those requests to the target server\n			ifk: rev_proxy forwards the requests of the client to the target_server\n				and give the result from the target_server to the client\n		the client is given an impression that it is connecting to the actual server, but in reality there exists a reverse proxy residing between the client and the actual server\n		ex:\n			when u_re connecting to google, you are only connecting to a reverse proxy\n		this is a bit hard, then it_s not really important to understand all of the rev_proxy at the starting_time\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-21 02:31:59'),(418,'myip from#grc.com','41.204.119.10',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-21 02:52:29'),(419,'#network proxy_introduction #advantage','\nProxy servers can also make your Internet access work more efficiently.\n	by __caching__ sites in ur proxy_server\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-21 03:06:31'),(420,'#proxychains #intro','When you want two (or more) different proxies in chain\n	like: your_host <--> proxy 1 (TOR) <--> proxy 2 (HTTP or SOCKS4/5) <--> target_host\nYou may need it when the only way out from your LAN is through proxy server\nAnd you want to do that with some app like telnet\nyou can even access your home LAN from outside via reverse proxy if you set it\nUse external DNS from behind any proxy/firewall.\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-21 03:33:16'),(421,'#proxychains #conf','\nproxychains looks for config file in following order:\n	1) ./proxychains.conf\n	2) $(HOME)/.proxychains/proxychains.conf\n	3) /etc/proxychains.conf **\nifk: which means ./proxychains.conf can overwrite some conf in /etc/proxychains.conf\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-21 03:37:47'),(422,'run proxychains','$ proxychains telnet targethost.com\n  run telnet through proxy(or chained proxies)\nspecified by proxychains.conf',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-21 03:41:26'),(424,'#resolve through #proxychains','$ proxyresolv targethost.com',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-21 03:43:53'),(425,'#squid #conf','/etc/squid/squid.conf',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-21 03:48:15'),(426,'#proxy #squid#server #default_http_port','3128',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-21 04:02:03'),(427,'#definition #gateway','A node on a network that serves as an entrance to another network\nroutes the traffic from a workstation to the outside\n	that is serving web_pages\n\nsometimes, a gateway acts as a proxy_server and a firewall at the same_time\na gateway may be associated with a router\n\ngateway is an earlier term for router\n\nA computer system located on earth that switches data signals and voice signals between satellites and terrestrial networks\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2015-01-21 04:11:01'),(428,'#definition #mandataire#server','server_mandataire et server_proxy so